                  <date when="1922-05-09">9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> May 1922</date>
               </dateline>


               <salute>Dear Thomas Hardy,</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>Many times I have written to you each time, sensible of the liberty I was taking in
               intruding upon you, destroying my letter. For twenty years you have been a part of
               our life and through your thought and work we have often found something that made
               us, even in our most anxious moments, live and try anew.</p>

            <p>Only this week we have been re-reading a book of yours - for perhaps the twentieth
               time.</p>

            <p>For a long time I could not forgive you for "<persName ref="#ps:LittleFatherTime"
                  >Father Time</persName>" in "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1894_JudetheObscure">Jude the
                  Obscure</ref>", but now I would not have him out of the book if I could. He had to
               be.</p>

            <p>My lover - we have been with one another over twenty years I think - first read one
               of your books to me - the
               great<!-- LW: I've split the ref so it works around the page break --> "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1891_Tess">Tess of the </ref><pb n="2"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.2389_2.jpg"/>
               <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2389_3.jpg"/>
               <ref target="#bib:Hardy1891_Tess">d'Urbervilles</ref>" &amp; then we read "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1886_Mayor">The Mayor of Casterbridge</ref>". And then re-read
               them both. And so it has been ever since - reading and re-reading your many
               books.</p>

            <p>Just now I was reading aloud some of your poems, lingering especially over "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1887_ShelleysSkylark"> Shelley's Skylark</ref>", "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1913_ThePhantomHorseWoman">The Phantom Horsewoman</ref>" "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1899_Departure">Departure</ref>", "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1901_TheDear">The Dear</ref>", "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1909_GeorgeMeredith">George Meredith</ref>," "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1896_InAWood">In a Wood</ref>" "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1901_UnbornPauperChild">To an Unborn Pauper Child</ref>" -
               indeed lingering over them all. Thrilled by the superb closing lines of the volume <q><lg>
                     <l>But - a stirring thrills the air</l>
                     <l>Like to sounds of joyance there</l>
                     <l>That the rages</l>
                     <l>Of the ages</l>
                     <l>Shall be cancelled, and deliverance offered<lb/> from the darts that
                        were,</l>
                     <l>Consciousness the Will</l>
                     <l>informing till It fashion all things fair</l>
                  </lg></q> I simply <hi rend="underline">had</hi> to come in &amp; tell you of our
               love and reverence.</p>

            <p>A short time ago I <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2389_4.jpg"/>
               <pb n="5" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2389_5.jpg"/>
               <!--Letterhead as p.1--> became quite angry concerning you while reading again "<ref
                  target="#bib:Hardy1891_NobleDames">A Group of Noble Dames</ref>". "He detests
               women - he is most unjust to them" I ranted. But very soon afterwards I retracted "He
               understands them <hi rend="underline">too</hi> well - &amp; his <persName
                  ref="#ps:TessDurbeyfield">Tess</persName> is the tortured upholder of that
               (earthily-obscured) ideal of chastity which has always been humanity's star".</p>

            <p><persName ref="#ps:RichardRobertFrankHill">Richard Robert Frank Hill</persName> is
               the name of the editor of this magazine &amp; the lover who loves me &amp; whom I
               love. <persName ref="#ps:NurseOSullivan"><unclear>Nurse</unclear>
                  O'Sullivan</persName> is the third in our <persName ref="#ps:TH">Hardy</persName>
               reading circle. We all send you our deep respect and regard and we say as a prayer
               "God bless you, guard you, uplift you &amp; hold you in His love"</p>

            <closer>
               <salute>I remain yours faithfully</salute>
               <signed>Lala Fisher</signed>
            </closer>

            <pb n="6" facs="uoedh_hl_h.2389_6.jpg"/>


